# Changelog

When you complete work that should be visible to humans (features, fixes, breaking changes, notable refactors, new apps/packages, or deployment-relevant behavior), **update [CHANGELOG.md](../../CHANGELOG.md)** in the same change.

## What to log

- **Added** — New capabilities, packages, endpoints, env vars, or docs users care about.
- **Changed** — Behavior or API changes that are not fixes.
- **Fixed** — Bug fixes.
- **Deprecated** / **Removed** — When phasing out or deleting behavior.
- **Security** — Vulnerability fixes or hardening.

Skip trivial edits (typos only, internal-only renames with no impact) unless they affect contributors or CI.

## How to write entries

- Use imperative mood (“Add…”, “Fix…”).
- One bullet per logical change; link issues/PRs if the repo uses them.
- Keep **[Unreleased]** current: add bullets there first. When releasing, rename **[Unreleased]** to a version section with date (e.g. `## [0.2.0] - 2026-04-01`) and start a fresh empty **Unreleased** section.
- Follow [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/) section order.

## Check before finishing a task

If the user’s request altered behavior, structure, or documented contracts, confirm **CHANGELOG.md** reflects it before considering the task done.
